  ('lilburn-mansion', 'Lilburn Mansion', 'Ellicott City', '4744 Montgomery Road', 'MD', 39.2673, -76.7943, 'mansion',
   'A striking Gothic Revival mansion built in 1857 by iron magnate Henry Richard Hazelhurst, Lilburn is considered the most haunted residence in Ellicott City.',
   'Henry Richard Hazelhurst built Lilburn in 1857 and made a fortune in the iron trade during the Civil War. Tragedy struck repeatedly as he lost his wife and several children — one daughter reportedly died in childbirth inside the mansion. Hazelhurst outlived most of his family, dying in 1900 at age 85. After a Christmas fire in 1923, the gothic tower''s peaked spires were replaced with stone battlements, and paranormal activity intensified. Housekeepers have seen the apparition of a young girl in a chiffon dress playing in various rooms, and the same entity has been observed walking down a hallway accompanied by a male figure. The heavy dining room chandelier began swinging violently during a 1960 family event with no explanation. Cigar smoke drifts through the library when no one is smoking, sealed windows open by themselves, and a child''s crying emanates from an upstairs bedroom — one family''s dog refused to enter the second-floor room.',
   1857, 'https://www.hauntedrooms.com/maryland/haunted-places/haunted-hotels/wayside-inn',
