  ('jonathan-hager-house', 'Jonathan Hager House', 'Hagerstown', '110 Key Street', 'MD', 39.6375, -77.7257, 'museum',
   'The 1739 limestone homestead of Hagerstown''s founder, named by Forbes as Maryland''s most haunted place, with at least 13 documented deaths within its walls.',
   'Jonathan Hager built this limestone homestead in 1739 as a combination residence, trading post, and frontier fort in western Maryland. The house has nearly 2-foot-thick stone walls and two natural springs running through its cellar. At least 13 people are known to have died in the house over its 280+ year history. Since becoming a museum in 1962, visitors and staff have reported extensive paranormal activity: a cradle rocks on its own, a corn doll moves about the house unaided, a rocking chair moves without human aid, and temperatures rise and fall inexplicably. The Downin children''s spirits are blamed for cameras malfunctioning in the residence. A lady in green has been seen looking out the window or as a flash of green dress in the hall. A man in black is spotted around the house and elsewhere in City Park, sometimes sitting on the porch smoking a pipe. The city offers hour-long ghost tours that sell out annually.',
   1739, 'https://radiofreehubcity.com/2024/10/09/hager-house-one-of-marylands-most-haunted-places/',
   '["https://radiofreehubcity.com/2024/10/09/hager-house-one-of-marylands-most-haunted-places/","https://www.marylandhauntedhouses.com/real-haunt/johnathan-hager-house-museum.html","https://www.hagerstownmd.org/1129/Ghost-Tour"]', 3),

  ('millers-church', 'Miller''s Church', 'Hagerstown', 'Spielman Road', 'MD', 39.5917, -77.7483, 'cemetery',
   'A remote 19th-century church and cemetery in Washington County known for unexplained car trouble and paranormal encounters on the surrounding road.',
   'Miller''s Church sits on a lonely stretch of Spielman Road outside Hagerstown, surrounded by farmland and woods. The small church and its adjacent cemetery date to the 1800s and have long been the subject of local ghost stories. Visitors report their cars stalling or experiencing electrical problems when passing the church at night. Some have reported seeing figures moving among the gravestones after dark, and others describe an oppressive feeling of being watched when approaching the property. The most common account involves car headlights dimming or flickering near the cemetery entrance, returning to normal only after passing the church grounds. Local teenagers have long considered it a dare to visit after midnight.',
