  ('surratt-house-museum', 'Surratt House Museum', 'Clinton', '9110 Brandywine Road', 'MD', 38.7544, -76.8983, 'museum',
   'The 1852 home of Mary Surratt, the first woman executed by the US government, and a stop on John Wilkes Booth''s escape route after Lincoln''s assassination.',
   'John and Mary Surratt built this house in 1852, and it served as a tavern, post office, and polling place. The area was named Surrattsville in 1853. During the Civil War, the house became entangled in the plot to kidnap President Lincoln — weapons and supplies were hidden here. After shooting Lincoln at Ford''s Theatre on April 14, 1865, Booth''s first stop on his escape was the Surratt house to retrieve the hidden carbines. Mary Surratt was convicted of conspiracy and became the first woman executed by the US government. Museum director Laurie Verge, a self-described skeptic, admits she cannot explain the footsteps heard by multiple employees — on one occasion, five or six staff members all stopped talking and heard someone walk in the front door, down the hall, and out the back, but found no one. Verge herself has sensed a man walking out of a bedroom and staring at her. Mary Surratt''s apparition has been spotted floating around the staircase and on the porch.',
   1852, 'https://www.marylandhauntedhouses.com/real-haunt/surratt-house-museum.html',
   '["https://www.marylandhauntedhouses.com/real-haunt/surratt-house-museum.html","https://cnsmaryland.org/2009/10/23/lincoln-history-sparks-museums-most-haunting-tales/","https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surratt_House_Museum"]', 3),

  ('glenn-dale-hospital', 'Glenn Dale Hospital', 'Glenn Dale', '5201 Glenn Dale Road', 'MD', 38.9836, -76.8206, 'hospital',
   'An abandoned 1930s tuberculosis sanatorium in Prince George''s County, closed since 1984, notorious for paranormal encounters and eerie phenomena.',
   'Glenn Dale Hospital was established in the early 1930s to combat the tuberculosis epidemic ravaging the Washington DC area. The sprawling campus included separate buildings for adults and children, connected by underground tunnels. The hospital treated thousands of TB patients over its decades of operation, and many died within its walls. After closing in 1984 due to asbestos contamination, the abandoned complex became one of Maryland''s most notorious haunted locations. Explorers who have entered the deteriorating buildings report hearing echoing cries and laughter in empty hallways, catching the scent of burning flesh, and encountering shadow figures in the underground tunnels. Cold spots are common throughout the children''s ward, and doors slam shut on their own. The property is now fenced off and patrolled, but its haunted reputation persists.',
   1934, 'https://patch.com/maryland/laurel/top-5-haunted-places-in-maryland-419ec447',
   '["https://patch.com/maryland/laurel/top-5-haunted-places-in-maryland-419ec447","https://www.marylandhauntedhouses.com/real-haunts/","https://strangertravelsusa.com/haunted-places-in-maryland/"]', 3),

  ('maryland-state-house', 'Maryland State House', 'Annapolis', '100 State Circle', 'MD', 38.9789, -76.4907, 'museum',
   'The oldest state capitol building still in continuous legislative use, haunted by the ghost of a plasterer who fell to his death while working on the dome.',
   'The Maryland State House was completed in 1772 and holds the distinction of being the oldest state capitol building still in continuous legislative use in the United States. It served as the nation''s capital from November 1783 to August 1784, where the Continental Congress ratified the Treaty of Paris ending the Revolutionary War. The building''s most famous ghost is Thomas Dance, a plasterer who fell to his death while working on the building''s iconic wooden dome in the late 1700s. Visitors and staff have reported seeing his apparition in the old Senate chamber, particularly near the dome area where he died. Some accounts describe a shadowy figure moving along the upper galleries, while others have heard unexplained thuds and the sound of tools dropping from above. The ghost is most active during renovation work on the building.',
   1772, 'https://www.hauntedrooms.com/maryland/haunted-places',
   '["https://www.hauntedrooms.com/maryland/haunted-places","https://patch.com/maryland/annapolis/these-are-creepiest-most-haunted-places-maryland"]', 2),

