  ('concord-point-lighthouse', 'Concord Point Lighthouse', 'Havre de Grace', '700 Concord Street', 'MD', 39.5375, -76.0894, 'other',
   'An 1827 granite lighthouse at the mouth of the Susquehanna River, haunted by the famous Perfumed Ghost and shadow figures in the lantern room.',
   'Built in 1827 using local granite from Port Deposit, the Concord Point Lighthouse guards the entrance to the Susquehanna River. Its first keeper was John O''Neill, a War of 1812 hero who single-handedly manned a cannon battery on Concord Point during the British attack on Havre de Grace in 1813. Four generations of the O''Neill family served as keepers. The first documented paranormal report dates from 1889, when a keeper described a figure with glowing eyes staring through the lantern room. The lighthouse''s most famous spirit is the Perfumed Ghost — a somber woman whose presence is announced by an overwhelming floral scent. Author Ed Okonowicz documented locals seeing a slow-moving shadow in the upper windows at night, and a dark figure has been encountered near the memorial cannon at the tower''s base. A murder victim''s body discovered on the grounds in 1994 may have added another spirit to the location.',
   1827, 'https://www.hauntscout.com/places/united-states/maryland/havre-de-grace/concord-point-lighthouse/',
   '["https://www.hauntscout.com/places/united-states/maryland/havre-de-grace/concord-point-lighthouse/","https://www.southernspiritguide.org/a-perfumed-ghost-havre-de-grace-maryland/","https://usghostadventures.com/havre-de-grace-ghost-tour/"]', 3),

  ('rodgers-house-havre-de-grace', 'Rodgers House', 'Havre de Grace', '226 North Washington Street', 'MD', 39.5411, -76.0917, 'mansion',
   'A Federal-era mansion built by Commodore John Rodgers, a War of 1812 naval hero, with reports of phantom footsteps and spectral figures on moonlit nights.',
   'The Rodgers House was built in the early 1800s for Commodore John Rodgers, one of the most distinguished naval officers of the early American republic. Rodgers commanded the frigate USS President and fired the first shots of the War of 1812. The mansion sits on a bluff overlooking the Chesapeake Bay near the site where British forces burned much of Havre de Grace in May 1813. Before the sun rose on May 3rd, 1813, the British launched a harrowing attack — few buildings survived and many residents died in the fiery confusion. Locals report seeing apparitions near the old pier tiers, leftovers from a 1900s boardwalk, walking over the place where the boardwalk used to be on moonlit nights. The Rodgers House itself has reports of phantom footsteps on its grand staircase and unexplained cold spots in the parlor rooms.',
   1810, 'https://usghostadventures.com/havre-de-grace-ghost-tour/',
   '["https://usghostadventures.com/havre-de-grace-ghost-tour/","https://www.havredehaunts.com/"]', 2),

